[Patient] How much water should I drink daily?
[Educator] Aim for 8-10 cups a day, but listen to your body's thirst cues. 
[Patient] Can I have other fluids instead of water?
[Educator] Yes, choose low-sugar options like herbal tea or diluted fruit juice. 
[Patient] Is it okay to drink soda or energy drinks?
[Educator] Try to limit those, as they can have too much sugar and caffeine. 
[Patient] What about sports drinks like Gatorade?
[Educator] Those can be high in sugar and sodium, try to limit them. 
[Patient] How do I know if I'm drinking too much water?
[Educator] Watch for swelling in your legs or shortness of breath. 
[Patient] Should I drink more water on hot days?
[Educator] Yes, it's important to stay hydrated in the heat. 
[Patient] Can I drink coffee or tea?
[Educator] Yes, but limit caffeine intake as it can affect your heart. 
[Patient] How about alcohol, can I have a drink?
[Educator] Limit alcohol, as it can worsen heart failure symptoms. 
[Patient] Any special tips for staying hydrated in my situation?
[Educator] Try carrying a water bottle with you and sipping throughout the day.